label.name: Geographic Location
label.description: This field corresponds to the largest common name associated with the artifact, image, or site related to a natural feature. This field differs from Political Location in that it refers to more natural features on the landscape. Common entries include: river valley, mountain range, desert, plains etc.

label.name: Political Location
label.description: This field is used for specific town names, village names, or other identifiable locales. This field differs from Geographic Location in that it refers to more man-made features or designations.

label.name: Where Collected?
label.description: In some instances, objects have been collected at a specific place such as a market, store, ceremonial gathering. This information should be included here. If the only information you have is a town, village or similar name, it should be placed in the “Political Location” field.

label.name: Where Manufactured?
label.description: Some objects will be collected in one region of the world but actually manufactured in another. Although this information will also be included in the description field, specifics can be added to here for searching purposes. For example: The Guthe collection was collected in the Philippines, but many of the ceramic vessels were manufactured at specific kilns in Thailand or China. The kiln name, province, country should be added here.

label.name: Provenience
label.description: The field corresponds with the provenience information associated mainly with excavated materials. This can include mound numbers, unit numbers, test pit numbers, elevation, and anything else that has been used to identify the actual provenience of an object. For objects excavated at large sites such as Mound 34, Cahokia. The overall site name (Cahokia) should be entered into the Archaeological Site Name field and Mound 34 should be added to the Provenience field

label.name: Specific Name
label.description: This field is used for scientific names or type names. Examples include: Sus barbatus (for domestic pig); Stanley Tool Impressed (pottery type), Barton Incised (pottery type). It is not used for names such as plainware, redware, bison, horse, etc. These non-specific names should be included in the description.
